# Strict Go Module Architecture

Follow this structure for every application module:

```text
internal/modules/<module>/
  domain/
    entity.go
    errors.go
    repository.go
  usecase/
    dto.go
    <action>.go
  infrastructure/
    <adapter>/
      repository.go
  transport/
    http/
      handler.go
      responses.go
      routes.go
  module.go
```

## Layer Rules

- `domain` contains only business entities, domain errors, and interfaces/contracts.
- `domain` must not import `gin`, database drivers, infrastructure packages, transport packages, or usecase packages.
- `usecase` contains application scenarios and DTOs for those scenarios.
- `usecase` may depend on `domain`, but must not depend on `transport/http`, `gin`, or concrete infrastructure implementations.
- `infrastructure` contains concrete implementations of domain interfaces, such as memory, postgres, redis, external APIs.
- `transport/http` contains only HTTP concerns: parsing params/body, calling usecases, mapping errors to status codes, and formatting JSON responses.
- Handlers must call usecases, not repositories directly.
- `module.go` wires the module dependencies internally: repository -> usecase -> handler -> routes.
- `internal/app/bootstrap` creates the app/server and registers modules; it must not know module internals.
- `cmd/api/main.go` only starts the application.

## User Module Reference

For the current `user` module:

- Domain entity is `internal/modules/user/domain.User`.
- Repository contract is `domain.Repository`.
- Get-user scenario is `usecase.GetUser`.
- HTTP route is registered in `transport/http/routes.go` as `GET /users/:id`.
- Memory storage lives in `infrastructure/memory`.

When adding new behavior, preserve this direction of dependencies:

```text
cmd -> bootstrap -> module -> transport -> usecase -> domain
                              infrastructure -> domain
```
